[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Sternberg is a delightful 43-year-old woman who presents for further treatment of rectosigmoid cancer.  Mrs. Sternberg developed hematochezia and underwent her first colonoscopy February 15, 2010.  A 2-mm polyp was removed from the hepatic flexure (tubular adenoma low-grade dysplasia), and a large broad-based sessile mass was noted in the distal sigmoid colon described at 15-cm.  This mass was biopsied and tattooed.  Pathology demonstrated mucinous adenocarcinoma.  No further staging has been performed.  Mrs. Sternberg offers no other complaints, including no nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, weight-loss, fever, hematochezia, melena, diarrhea, constipation, or change in bowel habits.  She does note feeling more abdominal fullness over recent years.
Mrs. Sternberg has no chronic comorbidities.  There is no history of nicotine dependence, thrombosis, heart attack, stroke, cardiopulmonary condition, medication allergy, glaucoma, or sleep apnea.  She has no history of anesthesia reactions or bleeding disorders.

[end section id="20103"]

